\begin_layout Section
Real Numbers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we talk of functions,
 we talk of only real valued functions.
 So,
 it is important that we brush up our theory of real numbers done in junior classes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Definition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Any decimal fraction,
 terminating or nonterminating,
 is called a 
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Real Numbers
\end_layout

\end_inset

real number.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The set of real numbers is represented by the symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Rational Numbers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Every rational number
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Rational numbers
\end_layout

\end_inset

 can be written in the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\dfrac{p}{q}$
\end_inset

 where p and q are integers.
 The set of rational numbers is reqresented by the symbol 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset


\series default
.
 i.e.
 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 = {
\begin_inset Formula $\dfrac{p}{q}$
\end_inset

 | 
\begin_inset Formula $q\neq0,$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 & 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

} 
\series default
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 is the set of Integers.
 The decimal representation of a rational number can be either 
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Terminating Decimal Expansion
\end_layout

\end_inset

terminating or 
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Non-Terminating Recurring Decimal Expansion
\end_layout

\end_inset

non-terminating reccuring.
 e.g.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.24 is a terminating decimal represenation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
5.
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{3}$
\end_inset

 is a non-terminating recurring decimal representation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Properties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The set of rational numbers is 
\series bold
closed
\series default
 with respect to the operations of addition,
 subtraction and product.
 i.e.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 are two rational numbers,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $p+q$
\end_inset

 ,
 
\begin_inset Formula $p-q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $pq$
\end_inset

 are rational.
 Also 
\begin_inset Formula $\dfrac{p}{q}$
\end_inset

 is rational provided 
\begin_inset Formula $q\neq0$
\end_inset

.
\series bold
[
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Closure Property of Rational Numbers
\end_layout

\end_inset

Closure Property]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Between any two rational numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 & 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 ,
 there exist infinite rational numbers.[
\series bold
Property of Denseness
\series default
]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Q.
 Find all the rational values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\sqrt{x^{2}+x+5}$
\end_inset

 is a rational number.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
Sol.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are rational numbers .
 Then the sum 
\begin_inset Formula $x+y=q$
\end_inset

 is a rational number.We now express 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y+x=\sqrt{x^{2}+x+5}+x=q
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sqrt{x^{2}+x+5}=q-x
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{2}+x+5=q^{2}-2qx+x^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=\frac{q^{2}-5}{1+2q},q\neq-\frac{1}{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
To prove the reverse i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\sqrt{x^{2}+x+5}$
\end_inset

 is a rational number if 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\dfrac{q^{2}-5}{1+2q},q\neq-\dfrac{1}{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
Its easy to check
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y=\sqrt{x^{2}+x+5}=\sqrt{\left(\frac{q^{2}-5}{1+2q}\right)^{2}+\left(\frac{q^{2}-5}{1+2q}\right)+5}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\sqrt{\frac{q^{4}+2q^{3}+11q^{2}+10q+25}{\left(1+2q\right)^{2}}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\sqrt{\left(\frac{q^{2}+q+5}{1+2q}\right)^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
It may be observed that 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{2}+q+5$
\end_inset

 is positive for all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

.Hence 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y=\frac{q^{2}+q+5}{|1+2q|}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
which is rational for 
\begin_inset Formula $q\neq-\dfrac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size footnotesize
Note :
 The sole purpose of adding 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 was to eliminate the square term of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 .
 The same goal can be achieved by subtracting 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Irrational Numbers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Non terminiating Non-recurring decimal Expansion
\end_layout

\end_inset

Non-terminating non-repeating decimal fractions are called Irrational numbers .
 In fact,
 all real numbers which are not rational are Irrational numbers.
 The set of Irrational numbers can be represented by the symbol 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{T}$
\end_inset

 
\series default
or 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}-\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 .
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Properties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The sum,difference,product and quotient of two Irrational numbers may be rational or irrational.ie.
 The set 
\series bold
T 
\series default
is not closed with respect to addition,subtraction,multiplication and division.
\series bold
[Closure Property
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Closure Property of Irrational Numbers
\end_layout

\end_inset

]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The sum,
 difference,product and quotient of a rational number and an Irrational number is Irrational.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There exist infinite rational and irrational numbers between two real numbers.
\series bold
[Property of Denseness
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Property of Denseness
\end_layout

\end_inset

]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Q.
 Prove that for every rational number 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{2}<3$
\end_inset

 one can always find a larger rational number 
\begin_inset Formula $r+k(k>0)$
\end_inset

for which 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(r+k\right)^{2}<3$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
Sol.
 We know,
 there exist infinite rational numbers between a rational number and an irrational number.
 So,
 there will be infinite rational numbers between 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{3}$
\end_inset

 .
 So,
 there exist infinite values of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 satisfying the condition.Let us take the case when 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is sufficiently close to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{3}$
\end_inset

.In that case,
 we can chose a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $k\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

.
 This implies 
\begin_inset Formula $k^{2}<k$
\end_inset

.
 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(r+k\right)^{2}<r^{2}+2rk+k$
\end_inset

.
 It is sufficient to put 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{2}+2rk+k=3$
\end_inset

.i.e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k=\frac{3-r^{2}}{1+2r}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
It may be observed that any rational number smaller than 
\begin_inset Formula $\dfrac{3-r^{2}}{1+2r}$
\end_inset

 in magnitude will also satisfy the condition.
\end_layout

