\begin_layout Plain Layout
The Wavey-Curve Technique
\end_layout

\end_inset

The Wavey-Curve Technique
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us consider,
 that we have an expression of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e=\dfrac{\left(x+1\right)\left(x-1\right)\left(x-3\right)}{x-2}
\]

\end_inset

 and we have to find the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 for which this expression is 
\begin_inset Formula $>0$
\end_inset

 ,
 
\begin_inset Formula $<0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $=0$
\end_inset

 .
 To find the sign of the expression,
 we first of all mark these points on the number line .
 Then we draw a curve like the one shown in the figure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename F:/DataBack/projects/Images/CC/M/1.1e/Images(Calculus)/ImagesReduced/GraphicWavey-Curve.jpg
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start from the right hand side ,
 draw a positive section of curve between 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

 and the right most point.
 Then,
 at the rightmost point( 3 in this case) ,
 we switch the sign of the curve to negative and take it below the axis.
 Like this ,
 we change sign of the curve at every 
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Critical Points in a Wavey-Curve
\end_layout

\end_inset

Critical point( ie.
 at 3,2,1,-1 in this case).
 Now from this curve,
 we try to find out the sign of the expression 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e=\dfrac{\left(x+1\right)\left(x-1\right)\left(x-3\right)}{x-2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $e>0$
\end_inset

 whenever + sign appears in the wavey-curve( i.e.
 when wavey-curve is above the axis)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow e>0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\epsilon\left(-\infty,-1\right)\cup\left(1,2\right)\cup\left(3,\infty\right)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The actual reason for the positive sign of 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(3,\infty\right)$
\end_inset

 is that in this interval the expressions 
\begin_inset Formula $x-3>0$
\end_inset

 ,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x-2$
\end_inset

>0 ,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x-1>0$
\end_inset

 and also 
\begin_inset Formula $x+1>0$
\end_inset

.
 Due to this reason,
 the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 which is obtained by multiplying 3 positive quatities and dividing the resultant with a positive quantity is positive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Similarly,
 in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2,3\right)$
\end_inset

 the quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $x-2$
\end_inset

>0,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x-1>0$
\end_inset

 & 
\begin_inset Formula $x+1>0$
\end_inset

 while the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $x-3<0$
\end_inset

 .
 Hence the expression 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is negative in this interval.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In this way we can investigate for other intervals also.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $e<0$
\end_inset

 whenever - sign appears in the wavey-curve( i.e.
 when wavey-curve is below the axis)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow e<0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\epsilon\left(-1,1\right)\cup\left(2,3\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $e=0$
\end_inset

 for all the critical points in the numerator( if and only if they don't appear in the denominator too)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow e=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\epsilon\left\{ -1,1,3\right\} $
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $e=$
\end_inset

Not defined for all the critical points in the denominator.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $e=$
\end_inset

Not defined for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\epsilon\left\{ 2\right\} $
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size footnotesize
{Note:
 It may be noted,
 that if we have to find 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $e\geq0$
\end_inset

 ,
 then we will take the union of the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 found out for 
\begin_inset Formula $e>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size footnotesize
i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $e\geq0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\epsilon\left(\left(-\infty,-1\right)\cup\left(1,2\right)\cup\left(3,\infty\right)\right)\cup\left\{ -1,1,3\right\} $
\end_inset

 .
 The same expression can be written by using a closed interval at the points where 
\begin_inset Formula $e=0$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $e\geq0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\epsilon\left(-\infty,-1\right]\cup\left[1,2\right)\cup\left[3,\infty\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size footnotesize
In a similar way,
 we can find the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $e\leq0$
\end_inset

.
 The solution is 
\begin_inset Formula $x\epsilon\left[-1,1\right]\cup\left(2,3\right]$
\end_inset

.
 }
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Example
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have to find the sign of 
\begin_inset Formula $E=\dfrac{\left(x+2\right)^{6}\left(3x+1\right)^{3}}{\left(1-x\right)}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To find the sign of such an expression,
 we first of all make the coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 as 1 in all terms.
 This gives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $E=-\dfrac{27\left(x+2\right)^{6}\left(x+\dfrac{1}{3}\right)^{3}}{x-1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The critical points of this expression are 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\left\{ -2,-\dfrac{1}{3},1\right\} $
\end_inset

 .
 The wavey-curve will start with a negative sign at 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

 as there is a - sign in front of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 The curve will then change sign at the first critical point -1.
 Thereafter ,
 the curve will change sign 3 times at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-\dfrac{1}{3}$
\end_inset

.
 (It may be noted that if a curve changes sign an odd number of times,
 it is equivalent to change of sign just one time) .
 Then the curve changes sign 6 times at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-2$
\end_inset

.(change of sign an even number of times means the sign is retained).Things will be more clear from the adjoining figure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename F:/DataBack/projects/Images/CC/M/1.1e/Images(Calculus)/ImagesReduced/GraphicWavey-Curve-Example.jpg
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow E>0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\epsilon\left(-\dfrac{1}{3},1\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly,
 
\begin_inset Formula $E<0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\epsilon\left(-\infty,-2\right)\cup\left(-2,-\dfrac{1}{3}\right)\cup\left(1,\infty\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also,
 
\begin_inset Formula $E=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\epsilon\left\{ -2,-\dfrac{1}{3}\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is not defined for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\epsilon\left\{ 1\right\} $
\end_inset


\end_layout

