\begin_layout Quote
h) 
\begin_inset Formula $|\cos x|=\cos x+1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\series bold
Case I
\series default
:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos x\geq0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow\cos x=\cos x+1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
which is not possible for any 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Hence ,
 no solution exists for 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos x\geq0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\series bold
Case II
\series default
:
\begin_inset Formula $\cos x<0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow-$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\cos x=\cos x+1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow2\cos x=-1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow\cos x=-\dfrac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 (which satisies our assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos x<0$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow x=2n\pi\pm\dfrac{2\pi}{3}$
\end_inset

 ,
 
\begin_inset Formula $n\epsilon Z$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
i) 
\begin_inset Formula $|(x^{2}+2x+5)+(3-5x)|=|x^{2}+2x+5|+|3-5x|$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula $|x+y|=|x|+|y|\Rightarrow xy\geq0$
\end_inset

(equality condition in Property 4)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
i.e 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 & 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are of the same sign
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
Now 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}+2x+5=\left(x+1\right)^{2}+4>0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow3-5x\geq0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
i.e 
\begin_inset Formula $x\leq\dfrac{3}{5}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $x\epsilon$
\end_inset

(-∞,
\begin_inset Formula $\dfrac{3}{5}$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
j)
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\left(x^{8}-4\right)-\left(x^{4}+2\right)\right|=\left|x^{8}-4\right|-\left|x^{4}+2\right|$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
We know,
 
\begin_inset Formula $|x-y|=|x|-|y|$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $xy\geq0$
\end_inset

 & 
\begin_inset Formula $|x|\geqslant|y|$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
Also ,
 it may be noted that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{4}+4>0\forall x$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

Our conditions reduce to 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{8}-4\geq x^{4}+2$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow x^{4}-2\geq1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow x^{4}\geq3$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $x\geq\sqrt[4]{3}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $x\leq-\sqrt[4]{3}$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x\epsilon\left(-∞,-\sqrt[4]{3}\right)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\cup$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\left(\sqrt[4]{3},∞\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
k)
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}-\left|x\right|-2=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow\left|x\right|^{2}-\left|x\right|-2=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow\left(\left|x\right|-2\right)\left(\left|x\right|+1\right)=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow\left|x\right|=2$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|x\right|=-1$
\end_inset

(Rejected)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $x=\pm2$
\end_inset

 i.e 
\begin_inset Formula $x\epsilon\left\{ -2,2\right\} $
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
l)
\begin_inset Formula $\left|x+2\right|=\left|x-2\right|+2\left|x\right|$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
We first of all find the 
\begin_inset Index idx
range none
pageformat default
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Critical Points in an Absolute value expression
\end_layout

\end_inset

critical points.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|x+2\right|=0$
\end_inset

 gives the point 
\begin_inset Formula $-2$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly,
 the points 2,0 are obtained by euating the other modulus terms to zero.
 So,
 there are 3 critical points ie at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\left\{ -2,0,2\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 We plot these points on the number line and divide the whole number line at these critical points.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename F:/DataBack/projects/Images/CC/M/1.1e/Images(Calculus)/ImagesReduced/Graphic-Modulus-Critical-Points.jpg
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\series bold
Case I
\series default
 :
 
\begin_inset Formula $x<-2$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
The equation becomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula $-\left(x+2\right)=-\left(x-2\right)-2x$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow2x=4$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow x=2$
\end_inset

 (which is rejected as it does not belong to the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(-\infty,-2\right)$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\series bold
Case II
\series default
:
 
\begin_inset Formula $-2\leq x<0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
The equation becomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula $x+2=-\left(x-2\right)-2x$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow x=0$
\end_inset

 (Which is rejected as it does not belong to the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[-2,0\right)$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\series bold
Case III
\series default
 :
 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq x<2$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
The equation becomes 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula $x+2=-\left(x-2\right)+2x$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
which is true for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 ,
 but our interval is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,2\right)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow x\epsilon\left[0,2\right)$
\end_inset

 is a solution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote

\series bold
Case IV
\series default
 :
 
\begin_inset Formula $x\geq2$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
The equation in this case becomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula $x+2=\left(x-2\right)+2x$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow x=2$
\end_inset

 (which is accepted as it lies in the interval chosen i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[2,\infty\right)$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $x=2$
\end_inset

 is a solution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
Now we combine all the solutions obtained from different intervals.
 So,
 the final solution is the union of all the cases i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x\epsilon\left[0,2\right)\cup\left\{ 2\right\} $
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

The complete solution set is 
\begin_inset Formula $x\epsilon\left[0,2\right]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
m)
