\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Case II
\series default
:
 
\begin_inset Formula $-\dfrac{9}{7}\leq x<-\dfrac{7}{5}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow-\left(3x+5\right)-\left(7x+9\right)=-\left(5x+7\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow-5x=7$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow x=-\dfrac{7}{5}$
\end_inset

 (which is rejected because in the beginning we fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $x\neq-\dfrac{7}{5}$
\end_inset

 .
 Also the point 
\begin_inset Formula $-\dfrac{7}{5}$
\end_inset

 does not lie in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $-\dfrac{9}{7}\leq x<-\dfrac{7}{5}$
\end_inset

 )
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Case III 
\series default
:
 
\begin_inset Formula $-\dfrac{7}{5}\leq x<-\dfrac{5}{3}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow-\left(3x+5\right)-\left(7x+9\right)=+\left(5x+7\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow-15x=21$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow x=-\dfrac{7}{5}$
\end_inset

 (which is rejected because in the beginning we fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $x\neq-\dfrac{7}{5}$
\end_inset

 due to domain restrictions.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Case IV
\series default
:
 
\begin_inset Formula $x\geq-\dfrac{5}{3}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow\left(3x+5\right)-\left(7x+9\right)=\left(5x+7\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow-9x=11$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow x=-\dfrac{11}{9}$
\end_inset

 (Rejected because 
\begin_inset Formula $-\dfrac{11}{9}$
\end_inset

 does not belong to the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $x\geq-\dfrac{5}{3}$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence,
 the only solution is 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-\dfrac{11}{9}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
n)
\begin_inset Formula $2^{\left|x+1\right|}-\left|2^{x}-1\right|=2^{x}+1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The critical points lie at 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|x+1\right|=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|2^{x}-1\right|=0$
\end_inset

 .
 i.e at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 So ,
 dividing the number line as done previously
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Case I
\series default
:
 
\begin_inset Formula $x<-1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow2^{-\left(x+1\right)}+\left(2^{x}-1\right)=2^{x}+1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow2^{-\left(x+1\right)}=2$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow-\left(x+1\right)=1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow x=-2$
\end_inset

 (Accepted )
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Case II
\series default
:
 
\begin_inset Formula $-1\leq x<0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow2^{x+1}+2^{x}-1=2^{x}+1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow2^{x+1}=2$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow x+1=1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow x=0$
\end_inset

 (Rejected as it does not lie in the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $-1\leq x<0$
\end_inset

 )
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Case III
\series default
:
 
\begin_inset Formula $x\geq0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow2^{x+1}-\left(2^{x}-1\right)=2^{x}+1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow2^{x+1}=2.2^{x}$
\end_inset

 ( which is true for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 belonging to the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $x\geq0$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

The solution to Case III is 
\begin_inset Formula $x\epsilon\left[0,\infty\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence,
 the general solution to this problem is 
\begin_inset Formula $x\epsilon\left\{ -2\right\} \cup\left[0,\infty\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

