\begin_layout Section
Logarithmic Differentiation(Revisiting Logarithms) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us first learn the basic definition of logarithms.
 First of all ,
 we have a exponential equation of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{α}=b$
\end_inset

 .
 This equation can be written in the logarithmic form as
\begin_inset Formula $α=log_{a}b$
\end_inset

.
 So,
 we understand that logarithms is just another way of writing an equation which has exponents involved in it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Logarithms have few basic properties :
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{a}p=\dfrac{\log_{b}p}{\log_{b}a}$
\end_inset

 (Base Change Formula)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{a}pq=\log_{a}p+\log_{a}q$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{a}p^{n}=n\log_{a}p$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Now suppose,
 we have a function of the form,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $y=f(x)=[u(x)]^{v(x)}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By taking logarithm (to base e) the above may be rewritten as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\ln y=v(x)\ln[u(x)]$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using chain rule we may dierentiate this to get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\dfrac{1}{y}.\dfrac{dy}{dx}=v(x).\dfrac{1}{u(x)}.u'\left(x\right)+v'(x)\ln[u(x)]$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main point to be noted in this method is that f (x) and u(x) must always be positive as otherwise their logarithms are not defined.
\end_layout

